## 11. CDD for Legal Persons, Enhanced Measures, and Periodic Updation

### 11.1 CDD Measures for Legal Persons (Other Than Natural Persons)

#### 11.1.1 Applicability and Procedure (Paragraph 4.3.1)

For the purpose of opening an account or establishing a relationship with a legal person (including sole proprietary concerns, partnership firms, companies, trusts, Non-Profit Organisations, and other juridical entities), the Company shall:

(a) Carry out Client Due Diligence (CDD) of the legal person in accordance with the procedure prescribed for individuals under Section 10 of this Policy (to the extent applicable);

(b) Mandatorily obtain and verify PAN from the issuing authority database in all cases;

(c) Additionally obtain the information and applicable documents prescribed under Rule 9 of the PML Rules, including but not limited to:

(i) Certificate of Incorporation / Registration;

(ii) Memorandum and Articles of Association (or equivalent constitutional documents);

(iii) Resolution of the Board of Directors (or equivalent governing body) authorising the establishment of the relationship and the persons authorised to act on behalf of the legal person;

(iv) Identification of all individuals authorised to operate the account;

(v) Address proof of the registered office or principal place of business;

(vi) Documents identifying the nature of business activity;

(vii) Such other documents as the Company may require based on the nature of the legal person and the risk assessment.

#### 11.1.2 Beneficial Owner Identification (Paragraph 4.3.2)

The Company shall ensure that the beneficial owner(s) are determined for all legal-person clients. All reasonable steps in terms of Rule 9(3) of the PML Rules shall be undertaken to verify the identity of each beneficial owner.

The identification and verification of beneficial owners shall include:

(a) Obtaining the beneficial owner's full name, date of birth, nationality, and address;

(b) Obtaining the beneficial owner's PAN;

(c) Verifying the beneficial owner's identity using reliable and independent sources;

(d) Documenting the chain of ownership or control between the client and the beneficial owner;

(e) Where ownership or control structures are complex, obtaining additional documentation to satisfy the Company that the beneficial owner has been correctly identified.

Where the Company is unable to identify or verify the beneficial owner to its satisfaction, the onboarding process shall be terminated in accordance with Section 7.2(d) of this Policy.

#### 11.1.3 Non-Profit Organisations and DARPAN Portal (Paragraph 4.3.3)

In the case of clients who are Non-Profit Organisations (as defined in Rule 2(1)(cf) of the PML Rules), the Company shall ensure that such clients are registered on the DARPAN Portal of NITI Aayog, as prescribed under Rule 9(9A) of the PML Rules.

The Company shall:

(a) Obtain proof of DARPAN registration from the NPO at the time of onboarding;

(b) Verify the DARPAN registration status through the NITI Aayog portal;

(c) Record the DARPAN registration details in the client's CDD file;

(d) Periodically verify continued DARPAN registration status as part of ongoing due diligence.

### 11.2 Enhanced Measures Under CDD

#### 11.2.1 Application Basis (Paragraph 4.4.1)

The Company shall apply enhanced measures under Client Due Diligence (CDD) based on materiality and risk. Such measures shall be initiated for transactions assessed as high risk, or where ML/TF/PF concerns arise based on any of the red-flag indicators triggered.

Enhanced measures under CDD mean applying measures and procedures that are more rigorous and robust than standard CDD and KYC processes. The scope and intensity of enhanced measures shall be commensurate with the risk profile of the client and the circumstances which triggered such measures. Enhanced measures shall not be limited merely to obtaining income or turnover-related documents.

#### 11.2.2 Indicative Enhanced Measures

In accordance with Paragraph 4.4.1 of the 2026 Guidelines, the following are indicative and non-exhaustive reasonable measures to be considered while implementing enhanced measures under CDD:

(a) Take measures to examine the financial position, including source of funds of the client;

(b) Take measures to record the purpose behind conducting such transactions;

(c) Conduct more frequent review of the client's profile and transactions;

(d) Take reasonable measures including gathering information from open sources;

(e) Undertake independent verification of the information obtained from the client and consult independent and credible databases, where necessary;

(f) Where appropriate, seek senior management approval for establishing or continuing the business relationship;

(g) Apply more stringent transaction monitoring rules to the client's account.

#### 11.2.3 Mandatory Application of Enhanced Measures (Paragraph 4.4.2)

The Company shall mandatorily apply enhanced measures under CDD to relationships and transactions in the following cases:

(a) **High-risk jurisdictions (Paragraph 4.4.2(a)):** Relationships and transactions with natural and legal persons from known high-risk jurisdictions, specifically with countries designated as tax havens and those on the FATF grey and black lists;

(b) **Politically Exposed Persons (Paragraph 4.4.2(b)):** When establishing a relationship with a Politically Exposed Person (PEP) as defined in Rule 2(1)(db) of the PML Rules. For the purposes of these provisions, the term PEP includes the natural person, immediate family members, and close associates as defined in the PML Rules;

(c) **Non-Profit Organisations (Paragraph 4.4.2(c)):** When establishing or maintaining a relationship with a client who is a Non-Profit Organisation as defined in Rule 2(1)(cf) of the PML Rules.

(d) **Cross-border element:** In light of the Company's cross-border customer profile, the Company shall also apply enhanced measures under CDD to:

(i) NRI clients with bank accounts or significant presence outside India;

(ii) Foreign-domiciled clients (whether individual or institutional);

(iii) Transactions involving counterparties or beneficiaries outside India;

(iv) Clients with multi-jurisdictional control or ownership structures.
